The paper discusses the performance of a convolutional neural network (CNN) in detecting signals in Poisson noise, which is a common problem in computer vision and image processing. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also compares the CNN performance with that of a Bayesian ideal observer and a linear support vector machine, which suggests that it may also belong to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing the sensitivity of the CNN to different types of stimuli, which could fall under sub-categories such as cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.IT (Information Theory).
